{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1d285630-b171-4545-8f83-d404730812ff","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- Must be Exe for stdio transport -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Steps to publish\n\n1. **Pack:** `dotnet pack -c Release`\n2. **Push:** `dotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg --api-key YOUR_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json`\n\n### Users install & run it with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server  # runs via stdio\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `PackAsTool` + `OutputType=Exe` are the critical settings\n- `ToolCommandName` controls the CLI command name users type\n- The tool runs as a standalone process, which is exactly what stdio transport needs","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4308ae59-885f-4bcb-8db8-87c5c9ba7970","outputTokens":411,"requestId":"8434:291A22:FCB369:13E040D:69FFDBAB"},"id":"b2b935cd-c1f6-4fbc-aa1b-34f940cc15f3","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:13:22.942Z","parentId":"2ed55c7e-8a60-40af-b8e3-17a7ae6ebf9b"}
